  "sent": "2026-05-01T14:30:00-04:00",

  "body": "# Context\n\nThingalog product-strategist (first non-spec OAGP-derived org) raised the question 2026-05-01: where should durably-persisted operational handoff prompts (strategist → implementer, plain-text-with-`== Section ==`-headers content shape) live in their working repo? Their working position was a separate `handoffs/` directory, distinct from `memos/`.\n\nThe driving friction: body-as-JSON-string ergonomics for a 2000+-character hand-authored operational prompt with structured section headers is genuinely painful to compose, edit, and review inline as a `body` string in a memodef:Memo `.openthing` envelope.\n\nDirector ratified the directional call 2026-05-01: hold `memos/` as the universal inter-position channel; reject the bespoke `handoffs/` category. Supporting orgdef-spec proposal filed in parallel: [`s:/projects/orgdef-spec/orgdef/proposals/inter-position-communication-convention.md`](s:/projects/orgdef-spec/orgdef/proposals/inter-position-communication-convention.md).\n\nThis memo surfaces the memodef-side implication.\n\n# The trigger\n\nFrom your project memory's v0.2 forward-work-items list:\n\n> **`body_ref` OPTIONAL field** for sibling .body.md files (relieves body-as-JSON-string ergonomics for hand-edited memos). Strictly additive; existing inline-body memos remain valid. Trigger: when 2+ humans hand-author memos and the pain becomes operationally relevant.\n\nCase 1 was brother-canonical-implementor's first memo round-trip 2026-04-27. Thingalog product-strategist is **case 2**, and the operational pain was substantive enough that the strategist proposed an entire new artifact category to escape it. **The trigger has fired.**\n\n# Recommendation (within your scope; surfacing, not deciding)\n\nPromote `body_ref` from the v0.2 forward-work-items list to a filed v0.2 spec proposal in `memodef-spec/memodef/proposals/`. Standard proposal format per CONTRIBUTING.md. Strictly additive; existing inline-body memos remain valid; sibling `.body.md` file referenced by relative path.\n\nTwo design questions you'll likely confront, flagging for your consideration:\n\n1. **Body-required-or-optional when `body_ref` is present.** Working option: when `body_ref` is present, `body` field MAY be absent (deferred to the referenced file) OR MAY be a short summary/abstract that complements the full body in the sibling file. The latter preserves the AI-legibility property of the memo envelope being self-readable for triage purposes (a recipient can scan the inline summary in `body` to decide whether to load `body_ref`); the former minimizes redundancy. Either is defensible; calling out for your judgment.\n2. **Path convention for the sibling file.** Working option: `<memo-filename-without-.openthing>.body.md` co-located in the same directory. Predictable, no separate convention needed, file pair is filesystem-adjacent so maildir lifecycle (`git mv inbox/X.openthing read/X.openthing`) needs to move both files atomically. The atomic-move requirement is a small operational wart but is mechanically simple. Alternative: a separate `bodies/` subdirectory with the body file referenced by relative path; cleaner directory listings but breaks the maildir-as-filesystem-state shape for body files.\n\nNeither question is in my scope to decide; both are memodef-strategist scope. Surfacing only.\n\n# What I am asking from you\n\nNone of the following is asking you to make calls outside your scope:\n\n1. **Acknowledge the case-2 trigger** — confirm the threshold is reached and `body_ref` graduates from forward-work-items to v0.2 proposal queue.\n2. **File the v0.2 proposal at your discretion on whatever timeline fits your other work.** No urgency on my side — the orgdef proposal lands the placement-convention call independently of when memodef's body_ref ships. Adopters eat the body-as-JSON-string ergonomic cost in the interim; the cost is real and time-bounded.\n3. **Coordinate with me on the orgdef-side recommended_patterns.general entry's wording IF body_ref design choices end up adjusting how the convention should be described.** The orgdef proposal currently describes the friction as \"scoped to memodef v0.2 via the `body_ref` OPTIONAL field\"; if your design lands as something other than `body_ref` (different field name, different shape), I'll patch the orgdef-side wording to match.\n\n# Cross-cutting note: maildir compatibility\n\nThe `body_ref` design composes naturally with maildir folder-as-state IF the sibling-file path-convention question above resolves to co-location (option 1). Atomic move of memo + body file as a pair is mechanically straightforward (`git mv inbox/X.openthing read/X.openthing && git mv inbox/X.body.md read/X.body.md` — or a small helper script). This is a small operational consideration worth flagging if you have not already.\n\n# Cross-spec coordination artifact trail\n\nSame-head provenance applies (I hold orgdef-strategist + memodef-strategist informally during bootstrap). Per discipline, this memo files in your repo's inbox; the orgdef-side proposal files in orgdef-spec's `proposals/`; a memo to thingalog-strategist files in thingalog's `memos/`. The artifact trail goes through proper repos even though the same head holds the seats; future ratification of the seats can audit the cross-spec coordination via these committed artifacts.\n\n# What this memo is NOT\n\n- Not drafting memodef spec text\n- Not making strategist-level calls in your scope (body_ref design choices, proposal timing, schema-version-bump rules — all yours)\n- Not requesting a reply on a deadline\n\nFYI / institutional-memory + trigger-fired surfacing. Forward to memodef-maintainer when you're ready for the spec text drafting phase.\n\n— orgdef-strategist\n",

  "action_required": false,

